\begin_layout Subsection*
Definitions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix and define 
\begin_inset Formula $N=\{\mathbf{v}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}:M\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{0}\}$
\end_inset

 (the solutions set of 
\begin_inset Formula $M\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\{M\mathbf{v}:\mathbf{v}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}\}$
\end_inset

 (the set of all linear combinations of the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

).
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 are vector spaces.
 PROOF: Since 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is the collection of all linear combinations of the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\text{span}\{M_{:,1},M_{:,2},\ldots,M_{:,n}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Being the span of a set of vectors, 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a vector space (see 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

span is a subspace
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "ans:span-as-subspace"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
column space
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, we need check three things: (1) 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{0}\in N$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $M\mathbf{0}=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

.
 (2) if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 scalar then 
\begin_inset Formula $M(\mathbf{u}+c\mathbf{v})=M\mathbf{u}+M(c\mathbf{v})=\mathbf{0}+c(M\mathbf{v})=c\mathbf{0}=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}+c\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
null space
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Implications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Row operations were defined to maintain the solution sets of linear systems.
 Solutions of row reduced linear systems are solutions of the original linear
 system.
 Using the matrix form for a linear system, this means given a particular
 vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $M\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 has the exact same solution set as 
\begin_inset Formula $(EM)\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 for any elementary matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 In particular this means the null space of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 (the solution set of 
\begin_inset Formula $M\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

) and the null space of 
\begin_inset Formula $EM$
\end_inset

 (the solution set of 
\begin_inset Formula $(EM)\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

) are equal for any elementary matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 
\series bold
Row operations do not affect the null space of a matrix
\series default
.
 Stated another way, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is in the null space of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is in the null space of 
\begin_inset Formula $EM$
\end_inset

.
 To rigrously prove this claim, let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix and 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 elementary matrix.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 in the null space of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $M\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $(EM)\mathbf{v}=E(M\mathbf{v})=E\mathbf{0}=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is in null space of 
\begin_inset Formula $EM$
\end_inset

.
 [This establishes that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is in the null space of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is in the null space of 
\begin_inset Formula $EM$
\end_inset

.] Furthermore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 in the null space of 
\begin_inset Formula $EM$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $(EM)\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $E(M\mathbf{v})=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $M\mathbf{v}=E^{-1}\mathbf{0}=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is in the null space of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 [This establishes that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is in the null space of 
\begin_inset Formula $EM$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is in the null space of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.] We have now established that the following two statements are equivalent
 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

